---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Writing" description="Long-form personal narrative from Sean Mandable.">
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-2xl">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">Writing</h1>
    <p class="mt-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700">
      Two long pieces of personal narrative — one from a mountain, one from a trail. Included here because the craft of noticing, which is most of what I do at a keyboard, happens to also be most of what I do when I'm not at a keyboard.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mx-auto mt-16 max-w-2xl space-y-12">
    <article class="border-t border-slate-200 pt-10">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">Memoir · 2011</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        <a href="/writing/no-hurry" class="hover:text-sky-600">No Hurry</a>
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm italic text-slate-500">Written from the trail in 2011.</p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700">
        In March of 2011 I set out to hike the Appalachian Trail, Georgia to Maine, and to live-blog the whole thing from an iPhone. I made it to Pearisburg, Virginia — about 650 miles in over three months — before coming home. This is the account of those months: the gear, the people, the weather, three separate encounters with hypothermia and a hypoglycemic seizure that nearly killed me at a shelter in the Smokies. Also the small unhurried mornings, the trail names, the unreliable cell service, the strangers who happened to show up exactly when I needed them.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700">A long read. I've split it into chapters.</p>
      <p class="mt-6">
        <a href="/writing/no-hurry" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sky-600 hover:underline">
          Read <span aria-hidden="true">→</span>
        </a>
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="border-t border-slate-200 pt-10">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">Essay · early 1990s</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        <a href="/writing/wilderness-challenge" class="hover:text-sky-600">Wilderness Challenge</a>
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm italic text-slate-500">A retrospective from the early 1990s.</p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700">
        An Outward Bound–style ski-and-winter-camping trip through the mountains of northern Idaho and southern British Columbia, taken as a required school expedition in January of my year at Rocky Mountain Academy. Seventy-pound packs, telemark skis none of us knew how to use, a broken ankle several days in, a makeshift sled, and a valley I still remember — dark on the right, sunlit on the left. "The valley of light and shadow," Christina called it.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6">
        <a href="/writing/wilderness-challenge" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sky-600 hover:underline">
          Read <span aria-hidden="true">→</span>
        </a>
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>
</Layout>
